1. We enable Docker support in `cypress.config.js` using the `@cypress/docker` package.
2. We customize screenshot settings, such as folder location, width, and height.
3. We create a custom reporter that saves screenshots on test completion.
4. In `cypress/support/index.js`, we set up tasks for starting and stopping the Docker container.
5. In `cypress/integration/example.spec.js`, we use the custom tasks to start and stop the Docker container in our tests.

Note that you'll need to replace `my-node-app` with the name of your Docker image. Also, you can further customize the screenshot saving logic in the custom reporter to fit your needs.

Run your tests using `npx cypress run` or `yarn cypress run`, and the screenshots will be saved in the `cypress/screenshots` folder.

Here's a simple implementation of a function that converts Markdown to HTML using the `std::stringstream` and some basic Markdown parsing. This implementation supports basic Markdown syntax like headers, bold and italic text, links, and inline code.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <sstream>
#include <string>
#include <regex>

std::string markdownToHtml(const std::string& markdown) {
    std::stringstream ss;
    std::string html;

    // Headers
    std::regex headerRegex("^#+(.*)$", std::regex_constants::icase);
    for (std::string line ; std::getline(ss.wrap(markdown), line); ) {
        if (std::regex_match(line, headerRegex)) {
            html += "<h" + (std::to_string(line[1] - '1') + ">") + std::regex_replace(line, headerRegex, "$1") + "</h" + std::to_string(line[1] - '1') + ">\n";
        } else {
            ss << line;
        }
    }
    ss.str(""); // Reset stringstream

    // Bold and Italic
    std::regex boldRegex("\\*([^*]+)\*", std::regex_constants::icase);
    std::regex italicRegex("\\*([^]*?)\*", std::regex_constants::icase);
    std::string temp;
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, temp, boldRegex)) {
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, boldRegex, "<b>" + std::regex_replace(temp, std::regex("\\*"), "") + "</b>");
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex(temp), ""); // Remove original bold text
    }
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, temp, italicRegex)) {
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, italicRegex, "<i>" + std::regex_replace(temp, std::regex("\\*"), "") + "</i>");
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, std::regex(temp), ""); // Remove original italic text
    }

    // Links
    std::regex linkRegex("\\[(.+?)\\]\\(([^\\)]+)\\)", std::regex_constants::icase);
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, temp, linkRegex)) {
        std::smatch match;
        std::regex_match(temp, match, linkRegex);
        html += "<a href=\"" + match[2] + "\" target=\"_blank\">" + match[1] + "</a>";
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, linkRegex, ""); // Remove original link
    }

    // Inline Code
    std::regex codeRegex("``([^``]+)``", std::regex_constants::icase);
    while (std::regex_search(markdown, temp, codeRegex)) {
        markdown = std::regex_replace(markdown, codeRegex, "<code>" + std::regex_replace(temp, std::regex("``"), "") + "</code>");
    }

    return html;
}

int main() {
    std::string markdown = "# Hello **World**!\nIt's an [example](https://example.com) of Markdown to HTML conversion. ``This is some inline code``.";
    std::string html = markdownToHtml(markdown);
    std::cout << html << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

Please note that this is a basic implementation and doesn't support all Markdown features. For a more comprehensive solution, consider using a dedicated Markdown parser library like `pugHeaderCode` or `Doxygen` (for Markdown support in Doxygen comments).

Also, this implementation assumes that the input Markdown is well-formed and doesn't contain nested constructs. For a robust production-ready solution, you should add error handling and support for nested constructs.

