You can solve this problem by using logarithms. In Java, you can use the Math.log function to calculate the logarithm base 3 of the given number. If the result is an integer, then the number is a power of three.

Here is the Java code for the problem:

```java
class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }
        double log = Math.log(n) / Math.log(3);
        return log == (int) log;
    }
}
```

This solution works because if `n` is a power of three, then `log(n) / log(3)` will be an integer. If `n` is not a power of three, the result of `log(n) / log(3)` will be a decimal number. The `(int) log` conversion will truncate the decimal part, so if the result is not an integer, it will be converted to `0.0` which is not equal to the original value. Therefore, we check if `log == (int) log` to determine if `n` is a power of three.

